<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1367,1897]" pageId="2" pageNumber="480">
<typeStatus box="[151,207,1367,1393]" pageId="2" pageNumber="480">Type</typeStatus>
data: According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Fox, W. J." box="[440,571,1367,1393]" pageId="2" pageNumber="480" pagination="63 - 70" refId="ref4568" refString="Fox, W. J. (1899) Synopsis of the United States species of the Hymenopterous genus Centris Fabr. with description of a new species from Trinidad. Proceedings of the Academy of Sciences of Philadelphia, 51, 63 - 70." type="journal article" year="1899">Fox (1899)</bibRefCitation>
, the two females he used to describe this species were collected by Annie Trumbull Slosson (
<date box="[367,498,1403,1430]" pageId="2" pageNumber="480" value="1838" valueMax="1926">1838‒1926</date>
), one of the few American female entomologists in the nineteenth century. Slosson made several biological expeditions, from 
<collectingRegion box="[623,805,1439,1465]" country="United States of America" name="New Hampshire" pageId="2" pageNumber="480">New Hampshire</collectingRegion>
to southern 
<collectingRegion box="[941,1025,1439,1465]" country="United States of America" name="Florida" pageId="2" pageNumber="480">Florida</collectingRegion>
, often accompanied by other naturalists. She used to donate insect specimens to collectors and taxonomists, like Fox and others. Her insect collection, composed by approximately 35,000 specimens, was donated by herself to the American Museum of Natural History (
<bibRefCitation author="Ifkovic, E." box="[159,316,1547,1573]" pageId="2" pageNumber="480" refId="ref4648" refString="Ifkovic, E. (2004) The life and works of writer Annie Trumbull Slosson-a Connecticut local colorist. Studies in American Literature Vol. 68. Edwin Mellen Press, Lewiston, New York, viii + 481 pp." type="book" year="2004">Ifkovic, 2004</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
